03931nam a22006375i 9780292739208DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014032144  a97802927392087 a10.7560/7391922doi  a(DE-B1597)588212  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPN1995.9.S26bB67 2015 4aPN1995.9.S26bB67 2015eb 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/6152231 aBrode, Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFantastic Planets, Forbidden Zones, and Lost Continents :bThe 100 Greatest Science-Fiction Films /cDouglas Brode. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (440 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe List: The 100 Greatest Sci-Fi Films -- tA TRIP TO THE MOON/ LE VOYAGE DANS LA LUNE (1902). PART 1 -- tA TRIP TO THE MOON/ LE VOYAGE DANS LA LUNE (1902). PART 2 -- tAppendices -- tGeneral Index -- tFilm Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhether you judge by box office receipts, industry awards, or critical accolades, science fiction films are the most popular movies now being produced and distributed around the world. Nor is this phenomenon new. Sci-fi filmmakers and audiences have been exploring fantastic planets, forbidden zones, and lost continents ever since George Méliès’ 1902 film A Trip to the Moon. In this highly entertaining and knowledgeable book, film historian and pop culture expert Douglas Brode picks the one hundred greatest sci-fi films of all time. Brode’s list ranges from today’s blockbusters to forgotten gems, with surprises for even the most informed fans and scholars. He presents the movies in chronological order, which effectively makes this book a concise history of the sci-fi film genre. A striking (and in many cases rare) photograph accompanies each entry, for which Brode provides a numerical rating, key credits and cast members, brief plot summary, background on the film’s creation, elements of the moviemaking process, analysis of the major theme(s), and trivia. He also includes fun outtakes, including his top ten lists of Fifties sci-fi movies, cult sci-fi, least necessary movie remakes, and “so bad they’re great” classics—as well as the ten worst sci-fi movies (“those highly ambitious films that promised much and delivered nil”). So climb aboard spaceship Brode and journey to strange new worlds from Metropolis (1927) to Guardians of the Galaxy (2014).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aScience fiction filmsxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73919240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292739208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292739208/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK